#loads package MASS and data cats from it
library(MASS)
data(cats)

1.

#Finds gamma parameters shape and scale given some mean and variance, and returns those as outout
gammafunction <- function(gamma.mean, gamma.var){
  a = (gamma.mean ^ 2) / (gamma.var)
  s = (gamma.var) / (gamma.mean)
  output <- c("a"=a,"s"=s)
  return(output)
}

#Runs the gammafunction built above to find the parameters a and s based on the mean and variance of the cat heart weight data (method of moments because chooses parameters based on the mean and variance moments), and stores those in catparams
catparams <- gammafunction(mean(cats$Hwt),var(cats$Hwt))
catparams
##          a          s 
## 19.0653121  0.5575862

2.

#Finds the gamma function value of each heart weight data point (f(x) for each x)
catdensities <- dgamma(cats$Hwt , shape = catparams[1], scale = catparams[2])
#Takes the log of each and then sums them to give the log likelihood
sum(log(catdensities))
## [1] -325.6886

3.

#Creates a function to find the loglikelihood (same process as above) based on the cat data with any input parameters a (shapeparam) and s (scaleparam)
gamma.loglike <- function(shapeparam, scaleparam){
  tempdensities <- dgamma(cats$Hwt, shape = shapeparam, scale = scaleparam)
  loglike <- sum(log(tempdensities)) 
  return(loglike)
}
#Runs the function with the parameters found by method of moments to get that log likelihood
gamma.loglike(catparams[1], catparams[2])
## [1] -325.6886

4.

#Creates a function so can run gamma.loglike on a vector of different a (shape) parameters, while holding s (scale) constant as what was found via method of moments
differshape <- function(x){sapply(x, gamma.loglike, scaleparam = catparams[2])}
#Uses the function just created to plot the log likelihood as a function of a
curve(differshape, from = 1, to = 40)

#This peaks at around -326 (around the same as just using the method of moments parameters) when a is about 19 (around the same as well)

#Creates a function so can run gamma.loglike on a vector of different s (scale) parameters, while holding a (shape) constant as what was found via method of moments
differscale <- function(x){sapply(x, gamma.loglike, shapeparam = catparams[1])}
#Uses the function just created to plot the log likelihood as a function of s
curve(differscale, from = .01, to = 1)

#This peaks at around -326 (around the same as just using the method of moments parameters) when s is about 0.56 (around the same as well)

The two maxima are approximately equal but not exactly. They don’t need to be since these are the maximum it can reach holding one constant while varying the other. The real maximum is found when we can vary both.

#Creates a matrix of log-likelihoods for various different combinations of a and s (all combinations of the two sequences given below for x and y)
z <- outer(X = seq(from = 1, to = 40, by=0.5), Y = seq(from = 0.01, to = 1, by=.005), FUN = Vectorize(gamma.loglike))
#Creates a contour plot based on those values
contour(seq(from = 1, to = 40, by=0.5), seq(from = 0.01, to = 1, by=.005), z, nlevels = 1000, main = "Log Likelihood", xlab = "a (shape)", ylab = "s (scale)")
#Adds a point where the method of moments parameters are
points(x = catparams[1], y = catparams[2], col = "red")

6. Yes, because those points are in the area that seems to maximize the likelihood. It can just be maximized more when one of them is not being held constant.

#Creates a matrix of log-likelihoods for various different combinations of a and s (all combinations of the two sequences given below for x and y)
z <- outer(X = seq(from = 20.1, to = 20.5, by=0.005), Y = seq(from = 0.52, to = 0.53, by=.00005), FUN = Vectorize(gamma.loglike))
#Creates a contour plot based on those values
contour(seq(from = 20.1, to = 20.5, by=0.005), seq(from = 0.52, to = 0.53, by=.00005), z, nlevels = 400, main = "Log Likelihood", xlab = "a (shape)", ylab = "s (scale)")

8. Based on these plots, the likelihood can only get around 0.14 higher than with the method of moments, to around -325.548. It reaches this maximum roughly around a = 20.3, and s = 0.524.

9.

#Modifies the function gamma.loglike from above to it essentially does the same thing, but this time has the parameters put in as one vector params where the first value is a (shape) and the second is s (scale).  Then it returns the negative log likehood so that when the function is minimized, it will be maximizing the original function
new.gamma.loglike <- function(params){
  tempdensities <- dgamma(cats$Hwt, shape = params[1], scale = params[2])
  loglike <- sum(log(tempdensities)) 
  return(-loglike)
}
#Runs the function with the method of moments parameters just to check
new.gamma.loglike(catparams)
## [1] 325.6886
#Runs optim on the new function to find what values of a and s minimize the negative loglikelihood (or maximize the log likelihood), and uses the method of moments parameters as the initial guess
optim(catparams,new.gamma.loglike)
